Travel Agents Record Growing Numbers of Bookings
It looks like winter will be good for German entrepreneurs in tourism:
According to one study, bookings for trips in the coming months increased significantly compared to the previous year - by more than 30 percent even in the winter season.
Despite weak economic growth, the Germans’ desire to travel remains undiminished.
For bookings for the winter season, travel agencies recorded an increase of 31 percent in turnover compared to the same period last year, according to the German Travel Association (DRV) in Berlin on Monday.
According to a survey by the GfK Market Research Institute, there are already increased bookings available for the autumn months.
According to DRV, the turnover was thus about eleven per cent higher in October compared to 2007.
The results are based on GfK figures, which evaluates booking data from 1,200 German travel agencies each month and interpolates them to the overall market.
This result included bookings of trips that took place until the end of August 2008.
Due to the weak exchange rate of the dollar, travel to the United States is mainly requested, the DRV said.
For these routes, the increase in bookings is about one third.
In addition, Spain, Turkey and Greece, as well as domestic waters, are particularly sought after by the Germans.
Above all, the organized tours are in course, said the President of the DRV Klaus Laepple.
In view of the increasing expenditure on energy and food, the costs are "easier to calculate for the client than for an individually organized holiday".
Laepple explained that, among other things, consumers can save money by using early booking discounts or all-inclusive offers.
Even in the summer months, the number of bookings was said to be very good, so there will again be higher turnover compared to the previous year - although according to another study, the number of Germans who made a trip has fallen compared to the previous year.
