The tour guides will tell you.
The building sits circumferentially at the end of the platform with a tower on each corner of the front, overlooking the indistinguishable from some provincial German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slowly falling apart.
But once one gets inside the vaulted cash register, one can no longer doubt the size of the enterprise whose westernmost gateway the station was.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German Consortium of Anatolian-Baghdadi Corporation.
Germany, which was involved in the late game of empires, intended to realize its ambition to control the Middle East using this railway, which was to lead to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond into what is now Saudi Arabia.
But the German imperial ambitions collapsed during the First World War.
Their trains were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular troops.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone
British and colonial troops advanced from Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there's bad news for Hydarpa<0xC5><0xA1> station, too.
In 1917, an explosion of a munitions train destroyed its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has been gradually squatting and history is circumventing it.
Today, however, this gate to Anatolia and further east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) has created a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding areas, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
Now a new policy is in place - Turkey is engaged.
It is remarkable that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to review the parameters of this new policy, I boarded a night train to the Turkish capital of Ankara, where I was to meet with one of the leading AKP foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a curling ride on the tracks, which reminded the old-world rhythms of the well-known document Night Post, I arrived in the Turkish metropolis, designed as a new city for a secular state that wants to go back to its Ottoman past.
But the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents a shift in the paradigm of the Turkish consensus.
There were suspicions in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi brought me to the main tent of the AKP, an ultra-modern stone and metal building, purposely built on a developing suburb, surrounded by semi-developed department stores and power shops, where middle managers in business dresses - men and women - meet to
Suat Kiniklioglu could easily be a centre-right politician from almost every other European political party.
Jacket, tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry, too.
“The party’s foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate surroundings.
The Cold War was an anomaly," he said.
Turkey was cut off from its ambush.
Today we have to look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't a choice.
He must have done both.
"But there will surely come a time," I asked, "when will Turkey possibly have to decide?"
"Turkey," he said, "did not wish that such a decision had to be made."
He then stressed what almost everyone I spoke to here said almost in memory: Turkey's relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea area are just as beneficial to Europe and the United States as Turkey is.
With Turkey on board, it seems that Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, go along these tracks east to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at the Hydarpa<0xC5><0xA1>a station, after another mostly waking night, I thought of the two German lords Herr Ritter and Herr Conu who were watching this building being built a hundred years ago.
