"Car bee" prevents collisions
This time around, Nissan was inspired by nature, specifically by bees, to make progress in the development of accident-protection technologies.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes the model of flying bees, and thus prevents collisions.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C, which represents the first step in precipitation prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Nissan Motor Co. Robot Center for Technical Progress have developed, in collaboration with the Center for Advancement in Scientific and Technological Research of the prestigious Japanese University of Tokyo.
According to Kazuhir Doie, CEO of public relations for technology, research and development of the brand, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan’s four-zone safety shield.
The task of the robot is to strengthen the ability to prevent precipitation in cars of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of an oval shape, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
The most important, however, are the folded bee eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, allowing the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
When creating this visual feature, the engineers designed what they called the Laser Range Finder.
It records obstacles up to two metres in a 180-degree radius before BR23C, calculates the distance of an object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it to a collision warning.
"The moment an obstacle is detected, the robot mimics the bee's movements and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the right or even greater angle to prevent a collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is the fact that all maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to respond quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move upwards and downwards or diagonally, its movement is limited to only two dimensions and in a direction that is possible by rotating its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities as in bees.
In addition to acceleration and deceleration, Nissan also used the rotation function to prevent the robot from crashing.
"The device only needs to process the information every few seconds, and to preserve itself according to this data.
It does not require information or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption with just two dozen kB of memory.
You may be surprised, but we’re not talking about the gig or the mega.”
This is the first step in the development of new technologies for the immediate prevention of precipitation, a technology that Nissan predicts will be used in serial cars in ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be the integration of the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the driver to the destination while avoiding obstacles on the way.
