The fox in the chicken coop
Life and health insurance companies in America, based on people’s data on the purchase of drugs, often reject the possibility of entering into an insurance contract with the applicant.
Data protection experts are concerned that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection program that binds the use of prescribing data in any case to the consent of the person concerned.
It must be in the hands of someone independent, otherwise we entrust the chicken coop to the fox," Richard Dick, the author of the drug-prescribing program, told The Washington Post.
Insurance companies make insurance payments and amounts paid in the event of insurance incidents depending on the health of the interested parties, and if the risk is assessed as being too large, they will not insure with it.
Previously, they sent those concerned for medical examinations and concluded the contract only when they knew their results.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper procedure: based on the identification number, the customer from the pharmacies will easily find out what drugs he has bought in the last year and a half, from which the program itself derives, what he suffers from the disease and what his health condition is.
For example, if you regularly buy a large amount of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it indicates that it has practically uncontrollably high blood fat levels, which immediately places it in the category with a higher risk.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some of which determine the risk factor at the same time, so that the insurance company has almost no work left in addition to paperwork, although there are minor problems.
Disadvantages include the fact that licker drugs can also be used for several purposes, some compounds can be used, for example, against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
From the point of view of commercial insurance companies, these represent a significant risk-increasing factor, while the aforementioned problems are not.
For the purpose of requesting and processing the data, special companies have been set up to obtain the necessary information from the pharmacies and ask the patient for permission.
The authorities are now forcing them to do so, although they have not been punished for their previous negligence.
Some companies have recently been processing the results of laboratory tests, which combine data on the drugs used, thanks to which they can provide an even more accurate picture of the health of patients.
More and more companies have access to the data, and it will be increasingly difficult to control their use.
There is a special law on the protection of health data, but its effectiveness applies only to health service providers and insurance companies.
The bill, which gives the authorities the power to control even companies specializing in providing data, is before Congress.
Richard Dick acknowledges that this is not enough: that is why he developed his program so that the transfer of data is tied to the express consent of the person concerned.
Another thing is that he can hardly refuse the permit in question, otherwise the insurance companies will not conclude a contract with him.
So the chickens are kind of referred to the fleas of good will.
